summary: natasha romanoff likes tony stark. she really does. he’s clever, and funny, and caring, and there’s more to him that meets the...
body:
natasha romanoff likes tony stark.

she really does. he’s clever, and funny, and caring, and there’s more to him that meets the eye.

and that’s why she doesn’t let him trust her.

she avoids him and ignores him, pushes him away any time he gets close, refuses to accept the chances he gives her and offers of friendship.

she brushes off how badly it stings when she sees the slightly crushed look on his face after a particularly brutal rebuke.

and sometimes, she thinks that maybe she should stop, that maybe she can trust herself this time, this one time, to take his trust and save it, to keep it close and never break it.

but she knows herself better than that, and she knows tony better than that, too, knows how he’s been betrayed and hurt, knows how badly he needs friends like rhodey and pepper, who are solid and dependable and kind and good, in every way natasha is certain that she never will be.

tony asks her one day, why she’s always running from him.

she looks at him, cold and careful, and slowly says, “i’m a spy first and anyone’s friend second, stark. do you know the price the plans for your suit could fetch, or even just a clue on how to rip off your armor and take a stab at your heart? it’s better for you that i don’t get attached.”

tony holds her gaze, and then nods, looks away.

“i’m sorry,” natasha says quietly, one last bit of truth before they go back to the distance and the lies and the ice.

“i know.”

title: Coffee & Books (book 1) - Loki fanfic
body:
read it on the AO3 at http://bit.ly/2UcmQF8

by ilse_writes

The people of Asgard are looking for a new home. They get a warm welcome on Earth, except for Loki. He is treated like a criminal of war, a terrorist. All they see in him is darkness. But there is a light, if she is up for the task.

Fragment:
At that moment, the door to the apartment swings open and a man barges in. He is holding something that looks like a big syringe in his hands. “Yoohoo… Reindeer games! You home? I’ve got something for you!”
The man stops in his tracks when he spots us sitting on the couch. “I’m sorry, I didn’t realise we had company. And beautiful company at that, I might say. What’s your name, beautiful? Do you have clearance? Williams, does she have clearance?”
[…]
From the corner of my eye I can see that Loki has turned his chair to face the room, watching the exchange between me and Tony Stark with a hint of a smile on his face. I get the sense that there’s not much that gets past the Trickster.
Mr. Stark has already moved on, walking towards Loki. He is holding up the syringe like it’s a Super Soaker gun, waving it back and forth. “This will only hurt a little, Bambi!” Tony laughs.

First published February 2018 on Wattpad.

summary: Think Again (When You Stop Freaking Out)
title: Think Again (When You Stop Freaking Out)
body:
read it on the AO3 at http://bit.ly/2DutvoJ

by Anika_Ann

Steve Rogers thought that seeing the aliens raining from the sky would be the craziest thing he had ever seen and nothing would top that.

Matt Murdock, on the other hand, was pretty sure he would never see anything again – after all, he had been blind for the past two decades.

Looks like they both needed to think again.

Well, that is after they get over the fact that something is seriously messed up here.

summary: The worst film in the MCU is Civil War because it convinced huge chunks of people on this website that liking Iron Man better...
body: The worst film in the MCU is Civil War because it convinced huge chunks of people on this website that liking Iron Man better than Captain America or vice versa is a political ideology. It’s not. They are superheroes. They punch bad guys. For this one special film they punched each other so we can debate ‘who would win in a fight ooooooo’. It’s for fun. It’s not serious. Stop calling each other imperialists and war criminal apologists. It’s not that deep and it never will be.
